<p>I would like to understand what happens in the following cases :</p>  <pre><code>bool b = false; float f = 3.14; char c = 1; int i = 2; unsigned int u = 3; long long int ll = 4; unsigned long long int ull = 5;  b += f; b += c; b += i; b += u; b += ll; b += ull;  b &amp;= f; b &amp;= c; b &amp;= i; b &amp;= u; b &amp;= ll; b &amp;= ull;  b &lt;&lt;= f; b &lt;&lt;= c; b &lt;&lt;= i; b &lt;&lt;= u; b &lt;&lt;= ll; b &lt;&lt;= ull; </code></pre>  <p>Or in other words, what are the implicit conversions that are done according to the standard?</p>  <p>Other questions: would the result be the same, if the only provided signature of compound assignment for an hypothetical <code>bool</code> class would be of the form:</p>  <pre><code>class bool {bool&amp; operator op=(int x) noexcept;}; // op &lt;=&gt; +,-,&amp;,|... </code></pre>